#: ../../R/Real-Programmer.rst:5
msgid "Real Programmer"
msgstr "Real Programmer"

#: ../../R/Real-Programmer.rst:7
msgid "n\\."
msgstr "名詞"

#: ../../R/Real-Programmer.rst:9
msgid ""
"[indirectly, from the book *Real Men Don't Eat Quiche*\\] A particular sub-"
"variety of hacker: one possessed of a flippant attitude toward complexity "
"that is arrogant even when justified by experience. The archetypal Real "
"Programmer likes to program on the :ref:`bare-metal` and is very good at "
"same, remembers the binary opcodes for every machine he has ever programmed,"
" thinks that HLLs are sissy, and uses a debugger to edit his code because "
"full-screen editors are for wimps. Real Programmers aren't satisfied with "
"code that hasn't been tuned into a state of :ref:`tense`\\ness just short of"
" rupture. Real Programmers never use comments or write documentation: \"If "
"it was hard to write\", says the Real Programmer, \"it should be hard to "
"understand.\" Real Programmers can make machines do things that were never "
"in their spec sheets; in fact, they are seldom really happy unless doing so."
" A Real Programmer's code can awe with its fiendish brilliance, even as its "
"crockishness appalls. Real Programmers live on junk food and coffee, hang "
"line-printer art on their walls, and terrify the crap out of other "
"programmers — because someday, somebody else might have to try to understand"
" their code in order to change it. Their successors generally consider it a "
":ref:`Good-Thing` that there aren't many Real Programmers around any more. "
"For a famous (and somewhat more positive) portrait of a Real Programmer, see"
" :ref:`The Story of Mel'<story-of-mel>` in Appendix A. The term itself was "
"popularized by a letter to the editor in the July 1983 Datamation titled "
"*Real Programmers Don't Use Pascal* by Ed Post, still circulating on Usenet "
"and Internet in on-line form."
msgstr ""
"[間接的に、書籍『Real Men Don't Eat Quiche』(\\ *Real Men Don't Eat Quiche*\\)から] "
"ハッカーの一亜種で、複雑さに対して、たとえ経験によって正当化されるとしても傲慢なほどに軽薄な態度を持つ者。典型的なReal Programmerは\\ "
":ref:`bare-metal`\\ "
"でプログラムを書くのを好み、それが非常に得意で、自分がプログラムしたことのあるあらゆるマシンのバイナリオペコードを覚えており、HLLは軟弱だと考え、フルスクリーンエディタは弱虫のためのものだからとデバッガを使ってコードを編集する。Real"
" Programmerは、破裂寸前の\\ :ref:`tense`\\ さの状態にまでチューニングされていないコードでは満足しない。Real "
"Programmerはコメントを使ったりドキュメントを書いたりは決してしない。「書くのが難しかったなら」とReal "
"Programmerは言う、「理解するのも難しくあるべきだ」。Real "
"Programmerは、仕様書に決して載っていなかったことをマシンにやらせることができる。実際、そうしているときでなければめったに本当に幸せではない。Real"
" Programmerのコードは、その悪意ある巧妙さで畏怖させる一方、そのいかがわしさで慄然とさせる。Real "
"Programmerはジャンクフードとコーヒーで生き、ラインプリンタアートを壁に掛け、他のプログラマを震え上がらせる。なぜなら、いつか誰か他の者が、それを変更するために彼らのコードを理解しようと試みなければならないかもしれないからだ。彼らの後継者たちは概して、もはやReal"
" Programmerがあまり残っていないことを\\ :ref:`Good-Thing`\\ だと考える。Real "
"Programmerの有名な(そしていくらかより肯定的な)肖像については、付録Aの\\ :ref:`The Story of Mel'<story-"
"of-mel>`\\ を参照。この語そのものは、Ed Postによる1983年7月のDatamation誌の編集者への投書『Real "
"Programmers Don't Use Pascal』(\\ *Real Programmers Don't Use "
"Pascal*\\)によって広まった。これはいまだにUsenetやインターネットでオンライン形式で出回っている。"

#: ../../R/Real-Programmer.rst:20
msgid ""
"Typing *Real Programmers Don't Use Pascal* into a web search engine should "
"turn up a copy."
msgstr ""
"『Real Programmers Don't Use Pascal』(\\ *Real Programmers Don't Use "
"Pascal*\\)をウェブ検索エンジンに打ち込めば、コピーが見つかるはずだ。"
